nodes.bodyText: The docker-compose files are different, so it's in theory possible to change these independently of what you see in the DbKVS tests. It could make sense to extract a common DbKVS TestRule for both the DbKVS and DB-TimeLock tests though I don't think we have the bandwidth for that now.

nodes.bodyText: I wonder if this the best we can do design wise, I feel like having these layers makes code a bit harder to read.

What alternatives do you have in mind? The main ones I'm aware of are:

passing a boolean and/or context directly into the testable timelock cluster (also OK with that, though it seems the property of whether you need a postgres is dependent on an individual server's config)
having a template variable that is the yml-serialized form of the database bound persistence (don't like this; the freemarker templates don't natively support structured formats other than xml and html I think)
I see, what you have now is fine.
I did not understand the comment, could you please elaborate on that.

There are some slow tests that aren't dependent on timestamp bound persistence (check where this is called), and so this skips them when running in a db timelock environment. This is only safe if we are sure it is tested elsewhere (which it is, because we will never test only db timelock when releasing).
It may be worth extracting out a utility method that takes templateVariables and needsPG as parameters? There is similar code in TestableTimelockCluster.
